We have the following identities:
$\sin(-x)=-\sin(x)$, so $1.\ \sin(-x) \leftrightarrow K.\ -\sin(x)$
$\cos(-x)=\cos(x)$, so $2.\ \cos(-x) \leftrightarrow$ there is no option for $\cos(x)$.
$\csc(-x)=-\csc(x)$, so $3.\ \csc(-x) \leftrightarrow J.\ -\csc(x)$
$\sec(x)=\frac{1}{\cos(x)}$, so $4.\ \sec(x) \leftrightarrow F.\ \frac{1}{\cos(x)}$
$\sec^2(x)=\frac{1}{\cos^2(x)}$, so $5.\ \sec^2(x) \leftrightarrow$ there is no option for $\frac{1}{\cos^2(x)}$.
$\tan^2(x)=\frac{\sin^2(x)}{\cos^2(x)}$, so $6.\ \tan^2(x) \leftrightarrow$ there is no option for $\frac{\sin^2(x)}{\cos^2(x)}$.
$\csc(x)=\frac{1}{\sin(x)}$, so $L.\ \frac{1}{\csc(x)} \leftrightarrow \sin(x)$.
$\sec(x)=\frac{1}{\cos(x)}$, so $F.\ \frac{1}{\cos(x)} \leftrightarrow \sec(x)$.
$\cos^2(x)=1-\sin^2(x)$, so $A.\ 1-\sin^2(x) \leftrightarrow \cos^2(x)$.
$\cot(x)=\frac{\cos(x)}{\sin(x)}$, so $E.\ \frac{\cos(x)}{\sin(x)} \leftrightarrow \cot(x)$.
$\tan(x)=\frac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)}$, so $C.\ \frac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)} \leftrightarrow \tan(x)$.
$\csc^2(x)=1+\cot^2(x)$, so $D.\ 1+\cot^2(x) \leftrightarrow \csc^2(x)$.
$\sec^2(x)=1+\tan^2(x)$, so $B.\ 1+\tan^2(x) \leftrightarrow \sec^2(x)$.
The remaining options are $G.\ \csc^2(x)-1$ and $H.\ \sec^2(x)-1$. We have that $\sin^2(x)=1-\cos^2(x)$, so $G.\ \csc^2(x)-1 \leftrightarrow \sin^2(x)$. We have that $\cos^2(x)=1-\sin^2(x)$, so $H.\ \sec^2(x)-1 \leftrightarrow \cos^2(x)$.
Thus, the matching is as follows:
$\boxed{
\begin{array}{c|c|c|c}
1 & 2 & 3 & 4 \\ \hline
K & \text{none} & J & F
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{c|c|c|c}
5 & 6 & 7 & 8 \\ \hline
\text{none} & \text{none} & \sin(x) & \cos(x)
\end{array}
}$
</think>

The answer is $\boxed{
\begin{array}{c|c|c|c}
1 & 2 & 3 & 4 \\ \hline
K & \text{none} & J & F
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{c|c|c|c}
5 & 6 & 7 & 8 \\ \hline
\text{none} & \text{none} & \sin(x) & \cos(x)
\end{array}
}$.

