Let the building have height $h_1$ for the first storey, and $h_2$ for the second storey, as shown.  From the given information, we have the equations \begin{align*}
\tan 20^\circ &= \frac{h_1}{51} \\
\tan 31^\circ &= \frac{h_1+h_2}{51}
\end{align*}Solving for $h_1$ in the first equation and substituting into the second equation gives $\tan 31^\circ = \frac{51\tan 20^\circ+h_2}{51}$.  Solving for $h_2$ gives \begin{align*}
h_2 &= 51\tan 31^\circ - 51\tan 20^\circ \\
&= 51(\tan 31^\circ-\tan 20^\circ) \\
&\approx \boxed{11.91}
\end{align*}[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (0,0);
B = (51,0);
C = (51,51*tan(20));
D = (51,51*tan(31));

draw(A--B);
draw(A--D,dashed);
draw(B--D,dashed);
draw(C--D,dashed);

label("$51$", (B/2), S);
label("$h_1$", (A + C)/2, W);
label("$h_2$", (C + D)/2, W);
label("$h_1 + h_2$", (A + D)/2, W);
label("$20^\circ$", (B/2 + C)/2, SE);
label("$31^\circ$", (B/2 + D)/2, SE);
[/asy]
</think>

The answer is $\boxed{11.91}$.

