The graph of $3^{-x}$ is shown in red and the graph of $x-2$ is shown in blue.  The graphs do not intersect, so there are $\boxed{\text{None}}$ solutions to the equation $3^{-x}=x-2$.

[asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

real func1(real x) {
  return(exp(-ln(3)*x));
}

real func2(real x) {
  return(x - 2);
}

int i;

draw(graph(func1,-2,3),red);
draw(graph(func2,-2,3),blue);
draw((-2,0)--(3,0));
draw((0,-2)--(0,3));

for (i = -1; i <= 2; ++i) {
  draw((i,-0.1)--(i,0.1));
  draw((-0.1,i)--(0.1,i));
}

label("$x$", (3,0), E);
label("$y$", (0,3), N);

dot("$(-1,-1.73)$", (-1,func1(-1)), NW);
dot("$(0,1)$", (0,func1(0)), NE);
dot("$(1,0.33)$", (1,func1(1)), NE);
dot("$(2,0.11)$", (2,func1(2)), NE);
[/asy]
</think>

The answer is $\boxed{\text{None}}$.

Let $F$ be the intersection of $DE$ and $AB$.
[asy]
pair A,B,C,D,E,F,P;
A=(0,0); B=(12,0); C=(8,16); D=(4,8); E=(10,16); P=(4.8,7.2); F=(8,0);
draw(A--B--C--cycle); draw(D--E); draw(A--P--B);
label("$A$",A,SW); label("$B$",B,SE); label("$C$",C,N); label("$D$",D,W); label("$E$",E,E); label("$F$",F,S); label("$P$",P,NW);
[/asy]
Because $DE\parallel AB$, $\triangle{FDE}\sim\triangle{FAB}$, and thus\[\frac{FE}{FA}=\frac{DE}{AB}=\frac{FD}{FB}.\]Let $k=\frac{FE}{FA}=\frac{DE}{AB}=\frac{FD}{FB}$. Then $FE=kFA$, $DE=kAB$, and $FD=kFB$.
Let $x=[ABC]$, $y=[FED]$, and $z=[FDP]$. We can express $[FAB]$ and $[FDE]$ in terms of $x,y,z$. First,\[[FAB]=\frac{FA}{FA+FE}\cdot \frac{FB}{FA+FE}\cdot [FED]+\frac{FA}{FA+FE}\cdot\frac{FE}{FA+FE}\cdot[FED]+\frac{FE}{FA+FE}\cdot\frac{FB}{FA+FE}\cdot[FED]+\frac{FE}{FA+FE}\cdot\frac{FE}{FA+FE}\cdot[FED]\]Since $FE=kFA$ and $k=\frac{FE}{FA}$, we have $\frac{FE}{FA+FE}=\frac{k}{1+k}$ and $\frac{FA}{FA+FE}=\frac{1}{1+k}$. Therefore,\[[FAB]=\left(\frac{1}{1+k}\right)^2y+\left(\frac{1}{1+k}\right)\left(\frac{k}{1+k}\right)y+\left(\frac{k}{1+k}\right)\left(\frac{1}{1+k}\right)y+\left(\frac{k}{1+k}\right)^2y=\frac{(1+k)^2y}{(1+k)^2}=\frac{y}{1+k}\]Now, $[FDP]=z$ and $[FEB]=\frac{k}{1+k}y$, so\[[FEB]=\frac{FB}{FA+FE}\cdot [FED]+\frac{FE}{FA+FE}\cdot [FED]=\frac{FB}{FA+FE}\cdot y+\frac{FE}{FA+FE}\cdot y=\left(\frac{k}{1+k}+\frac{1}{1+k}\right)y=\frac{k+1}{1+k}y=y\left(\frac{k}{1+k}+\frac{1}{1+k}\right)=y\]Therefore,\[[FAB]=\frac{y}{1+k}=\frac{36}{1+k}\]and\[[FED]=y=25.\]Substituting $25$ for $y$ gives $36=\frac{25}{1+k}$, so $1+k=\frac{25}{36}$ and $k=\frac{25}{36}-1=-\frac{11}{36}$.
Let $w=[ABP]$, and $v=[EAP]$. Then\[[EAP]=\frac{AE}{AF}\cdot [ABP]+\frac{EP}{AF}\cdot [ABP]\]Since $AE=\frac{1}{1+k}AB$, we have $\frac{AE}{AF}=\frac{1}{1+k}$. Therefore,\[v=\frac{1}{1+k}w+\frac{EP}{AF}\cdot w=\frac{1}{1+k}w+\frac{EP}{AF}\cdot w=\frac{1}{1+k}w+\frac{EP}{AF}\cdot w=\frac{w}{1+k}+\frac{EP}{AF}\cdot w\]Because $[FEP]=z$ and $z=\frac{k}{1+k}w$, we have $\frac{EP}{AF}=\frac{k}{1+k}$. Therefore,\[v=\frac{w}{1+k}+\frac{k}{1+k}\cdot w=\frac{1}{1+k}w+\frac{k}{1+k}\cdot w=\frac{k+1}{1+k}w=w\]Therefore,\[[EAP]=v=w=[ABP]=36.\]Now,\[[ABC]=\frac{AB}{AF}\cdot [ABP]+\frac{AC}{AF}\cdot [ABP]\]Since $\frac{AB}{AF}=\frac{1}{1+k}+\frac{k}{1+k}=\frac{k+1}{1+k}=1$, we have\[[ABC]=\frac{AB}{AF}\cdot [ABP]+\frac{AC}{AF}\cdot [ABP]=[ABP]+[ACP]=36+[ACP]\]Because $[FED]=y=25$ and $z=[FDP]=\frac{k}{1+k}w$, we have\[[ACP]=\frac{AC}{AF}\cdot [FDP]+\frac{AC}{AF}\cdot [FEP]=\frac{k}{1+k}w+\frac{1}{1+k}z=\frac{k}{1+k}w+\frac{1}{1+k}\cdot \frac{k}{1+k}\cdot w=\frac{k^2+k}{(1+k)^2}w\]Therefore,\[[ABC]=36+\frac{k^2+k}{(1+k)^2}w=36+\frac{k(k+1)}{(1+k)^2}w=36+\frac{k}{1+k}w=36-\frac{11}{36-11}\cdot 36=36-\frac{11}{25}\cdot 36=36-\frac{396}{25}=\frac{360}{25}=\boxed{144}.\]
</think>

The answer is $\boxed{I}$.

