The projection onto the $xy$-plane is the region bounded by the lines $y = 0$, $y = -\sqrt{3}x$, $x^2 + y^2 = 1$, and $x^2 + y^2 = 4$. This is the region shaded in the figure above. In polar coordinates, this region is described by $1 \le r \le 2$ and $-\pi/3 \le \theta \le 0$.

Therefore,
\begin{align*}
\int \int \int e^{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}} \, dx \, dy \, dz &= \int_{-\pi/3}^0 \int_1^2 \int_2^3 e^r \cdot r \, dz \, dr \, d\theta \\
&= \int_{-\pi/3}^0 \int_1^2 \int_2^3 e^r \cdot r \, dz \, dr \, d\theta \\
&= \int_{-\pi/3}^0 \int_1^2 3e^r \cdot r \, dr \, d\theta \\
&= \int_{-\pi/3}^0 \left[ 3re^r - 3e^r \right]_1^2 \, d\theta \\
&= \int_{-\pi/3}^0 \left( 3 \cdot 2 \cdot e^2 - 3e^2 - 3e^1 + 3e^1 \right) \, d\theta \\
&= \int_{-\pi/3}^0 3e^2 \, d\theta \\
&= \boxed{\frac{\pi e^2}{3}}.
\end{align*}The answer is $\boxed{\text{E}}$.
</think>

The answer is $\boxed{\text{E}}$.

