Note that
$$\int_{0}^{+\infty} \frac{\sin x}{x(x^{2}+1)^{2}}dx = \frac{1}{2i}\int_{0}^{+\infty} \frac{e^{ix}}{x(x^{2}+1)^{2}}dx - \frac{1}{2i}\int_{0}^{+\infty} \frac{e^{-ix}}{x(x^{2}+1)^{2}}dx$$
Let us calculate the first integral. Consider the function $f(z) = \frac{e^{iz}}{z(z^{2}+1)^{2}}$. It has a pole at $z=0$ and $z=\pm i$. We choose the contour $C_{R,\varepsilon}$ shown in the figure below.

[asy]
size(8cm);
pathpen = linewidth(0.7);
pair O=(0,0), I=(0,1), P=(1,0);
D(O--O+10dir(45));
D((0,-1.5)--(0,1.5));
D((-1.5,0)--(1.5,0));
D(O--I,dashed);
D(O--P,dashed);
D(CR(0,1.5));
D(CR(0,0.5));
D(O--0.5dir(135)--0.5dir(-135)--cycle);
D(O--0.2dir(135)--0.2dir(-135)--cycle);
D(O--0.1dir(135)--0.1dir(-135)--cycle);
D(O--0.05dir(135)--0.05dir(-135)--cycle);
D(O--0.025dir(135)--0.025dir(-135)--cycle);
D(O--0.005dir(135)--0.005dir(-135)--cycle);
D("z=-i",O+3dir(135),N);
D("z=i",O+3dir(45),N);
D("z=0",O+3dir(0),N);
D("R",1.2dir(45),NE);
D("ε",1.2dir(135),NW);
D(CR(0,0.9),linetype("2 2"));
D(CR(0,0.1),linetype("2 2"));
[/asy]

By the residue theorem, we have
$$\oint_{C_{R,\varepsilon}} f(z) dz = 2\pi i \cdot \mathrm{Res}(f,0)$$
where
$$\mathrm{Res}(f,0) = \lim_{z\to 0} z\cdot \frac{e^{iz}}{z(z^{2}+1)^{2}} = 1$$
Therefore,
$$\int_{R} f(z) dz + \int_{\varepsilon} f(z) dz + \int_{\varepsilon} f(z) dz + \int_{R} f(z) dz = 2\pi i$$
It is easy to prove that $\int_{R} f(z) dz \to 0$ as $R\to +\infty$, and $\int_{\varepsilon} f(z) dz \to -\frac{\pi}{2}i$ as $\varepsilon\to 0^{+}$. Therefore,
$$\int_{0}^{+\infty} \frac{e^{ix}}{x(x^{2}+1)^{2}}dx = \frac{\pi}{2}i$$
By the same method, we have
$$\int_{0}^{+\infty} \frac{e^{-ix}}{x(x^{2}+1)^{2}}dx = \frac{\pi}{2}i\left(1-\frac{3}{e}\right)$$
Therefore,
$$\int_{0}^{+\infty} \frac{\sin x}{x(x^{2}+1)^{2}}dx = \boxed{\frac{\pi}{2}\left( 1-\frac{3}{e} \right)}$$
</think>

The answer is $\boxed{B}$.

