label("$\left(\sqrt{6},2\right)$",(sqrt(6),2),NE);
label("$\left(0,0\right)$",(0,0),SW);
[/asy]

We find the $x$-coordinates of the intersection points of $y = 4x^2$ and $y = 2$ by setting $4x^2 = 2$, which gives $x = \pm\sqrt{\frac{1}{2}}$.  Similarly, we find the $x$-coordinates of the intersection points of $y = \frac{x^2}{3}$ and $y = 2$ by setting $\frac{x^2}{3} = 2$, which gives $x = \pm\sqrt{6}$.  Thus, the area of the shaded region is
\begin{align*}
\int_{-\sqrt{6}}^{-\sqrt{1/2}} \left(2 - \frac{x^2}{3}\right) \, dx + \int_{-\sqrt{1/2}}^{\sqrt{1/2}} \left(2 - 4x^2\right) \, dx + \int_{\sqrt{1/2}}^{\sqrt{6}} \left(2 - \frac{x^2}{3}\right) \, dx &= \frac{2}{3} \int_{-\sqrt{6}}^{\sqrt{6}} \left(3 - \frac{x^2}{2}\right) \, dx - \int_{-\sqrt{1/2}}^{\sqrt{1/2}} 4x^2 \, dx \\
&= 2 \int_{0}^{\sqrt{6}} \left(3 - \frac{x^2}{2}\right) \, dx - 2 \int_{0}^{\sqrt{1/2}} 4x^2 \, dx \\
&= 2\left[3x - \frac{x^3}{6}\right]_{0}^{\sqrt{6}} - 2\left[\frac{4x^3}{3}\right]_{0}^{\sqrt{1/2}} \\
&= 2\left(3\sqrt{6} - \frac{6\sqrt{6}}{6}\right) - 2\left(\frac{4\sqrt{1/2}}{3}\right) \\
&= \frac{\left(8\cdot\sqrt{3}-4\right)\cdot\sqrt{6}}{3}.
\end{align*}The answer is $\boxed{E}$.
</think>

The answer is $\boxed{E}$.

