We can divide $f(x)$ by $x^2-5x$ by noting that $-x^3+9x^2-20x-30=-x(x^2-5x)+4(x^2-5x)-30$. Thus we can write
\[f(x)=-x+4+\frac{-30}{x^2-5x}.\]Since $\frac{-30}{x^2-5x}$ goes to zero as $x$ goes to $\pm \infty$, we see that $f(x)$ approaches $-x+4$ as $x$ becomes large in magnitude. This is the same as the end behavior of $g(x)$.  We also see that $f(x)$ has vertical asymptotes at $x=0$ and $x=5$, and that $f(x)$ has a horizontal asymptote at $y=-x+4$.

