Squaring a binomial is done by multiplying the binomial by itself, so we have: $$\left(7-8 {\sqrt{7}}\right)^2=(7-8 {\sqrt{7}})(7-8 {\sqrt{7}})$$Now we use the distributive property: \begin{align*}
(7-8 {\sqrt{7}})(7-8 {\sqrt{7}})&=7(7-8 {\sqrt{7}})-8 {\sqrt{7}}(7-8 {\sqrt{7}})\\
&=7\cdot 7-7\cdot 8 {\sqrt{7}}-8 {\sqrt{7}}\cdot 7+(-8 {\sqrt{7}})\cdot(-8 {\sqrt{7}})\\
\end{align*}Now we use the product of a square and a number, $(a\sqrt{b})^2=a^2b$, to find that $(-8 {\sqrt{7}})\cdot(-8 {\sqrt{7}})=64\cdot7=448$. Also, we use the fact that $-8\cdot7=-56$ to find that $-7\cdot 8 {\sqrt{7}}-8 {\sqrt{7}}\cdot 7=-56\sqrt{7}$. Putting everything together, we have: \begin{align*}
7\cdot 7-7\cdot 8 {\sqrt{7}}-8 {\sqrt{7}}\cdot 7+(-8 {\sqrt{7}})\cdot(-8 {\sqrt{7}})&=49-56\sqrt{7}+448\\
&=\boxed{497-56\sqrt{7}}
\end{align*}
