Let $x$ be the number of bookcases and let $C$ be the total cost. Then $C$ is a linear function of $x$, so $C=ax+b$ for some constants $a$ and $b$. When $x=2000$, $C=50,\!000$, so $50,\!000=2000a+b$. When $x=800$, $C=32,\!120$, so $32,\!120=800a+b$. Therefore, $1792a=17880$ and $a=\frac{17880}{1792}=\frac{447}{44.8}$. Then $b=50,\!000-2000a=50,\!000-2000\cdot\frac{447}{44.8}=50,\!000-2000\cdot\frac{4470}{448}=50,\!000-2000\cdot\frac{2235}{224}=50,\!000-\frac{4470000}{224}=\frac{1118000}{224}=\frac{27950}{5.6}$. Therefore, $$C=\frac{447}{44.8}x+\frac{27950}{5.6}.$$The selling price is $\$57.9$, so the total revenue is $57.9x$. We want $57.9x=C$, so $$57.9x=\frac{447}{44.8}x+\frac{27950}{5.6}.$$Then $$57.9x-\frac{447}{44.8}x=\frac{27950}{5.6}.$$We can write $57.9$ as $\frac{5790}{100}=\frac{579}{10}$, so \begin{align*}
x\left(\frac{579}{10}-\frac{447}{44.8}\right)&=\frac{27950}{5.6}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad x\left(\frac{579\cdot44.8-447\cdot10}{448}\right)&=\frac{27950}{5.6}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad x\left(\frac{25837.2}{448}\right)&=\frac{27950}{5.6}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad x&=\frac{27950}{5.6}\cdot\frac{448}{25837.2}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad x&=\frac{27950\cdot448}{5.6\cdot25837.2}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad x&=\frac{27950\cdot80}{25837.2}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad x&=\frac{2236000}{25837.2}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad x&=\frac{559000}{6459.3}
\\\Rightarrow\qquad x&=\frac{5590000}{64593}\approx865.7.
\end{align*}So the break-even point occurs when $x$ is approximately $866$ and $C$ is approximately $57.9\cdot866=\$50,\!113.40$. The break-even point is approximately $\boxed{(866,50113.40)}$.
</think>

The answer is $\boxed{(866,50113.40)}$.

